trails.name: Quicksilver History Loop
trails.summary: A loop route through scenic, rugged, hilly southeastern Quicksilver Park. During the late 19th and early 20th centuries, this area held some of the world's most productive cinnabar (mercury ore) mines. This loop visits several of these old mining sites.

trails.name: Quicksilver - McAbee Loop CCW
trails.summary: A hike on beautiful, grass and wooded San Francisco South Bay Area hills. There are expansive views of the populated Bay Area on one side, and unpopulated, pristine, natural scenery on the other side.

trails.name: New Almaden Trail
trails.summary: This is a foot trail that basically runs parallel to Mine Hill Trail but at a slightly lower elevation. Unlike Mine Hill Trail that allows horses, New Almaden Trail is for foot travel only. The west end terminus of New Almaden Trail is Senador Mine Trail near the McAbee entrance to Quicksilver Park. The east end terminates at the Mockingbird entrance to Quicksilver Park.

trails.name: Ohlone Wilderness Trail at Mission Peak
trails.summary: This route takes you up to a saddle on the route to the top of Mission Peak, and it's a great trail with stunning views of the southern bay area. Hikers are rewarded with views of Mount Hamilton to the south, the Santa Cruz Mountains to the west, Mt. Tamalpais to the north, and Mt. Diablo and the Sierra Nevada to the northeast.

trails.name: Stanford Dish Loop
trails.summary: The Stanford Dish Loop Trail is a popular, paved trail that hikers and runners use for recreational purposes. The trail follows rises and falls along the hills above Stanford University, where various research and academics projects are happening.
